{{Quote|May the spirits of our ancestors watch over you and your troops.''"<br />"''As long as this old thing holds together, we'll be okay.|A Kaleesh holy man and Grievous|<ref name="Eyes" />}}
The '''''Martyr''''' was a [[Shuttle/Legends|shuttle]] used by the [[Kaleesh/Legends|Kaleesh]] [[Warlord/Legends|warlord]] [[Grievous/Legends|Grievous]]. The [[Color/Legends|gray]] shuttle had multiple [[Laser cannon/Legends|laser cannons]] and also functioned as a [[Troop carrier/Legends|troop carrier]], able to accommodate Grievous and all eight members of his elite [[Izvoshra/Legends|Izvoshra]]. By [[29 BBY/Legends|29 BBY]], Grievous and the Izvoshra took flight in the ''Martyr'' on Grievous's [[Homeworld/Legends|homeworld]] [[Kalee/Legends|Kalee]], planning to re-ignite the [[Huk War]] between the Kaleesh and the [[Yam'rii/Legends|Yam'rii]] [[Species/Legends|species]].

However, the shuttle was destroyed through [[Sabotage of Grievous' shuttle/Legends|sabotage]] planned by [[InterGalactic Banking Clan/Legends|InterGalactic Banking Clan]] [[Chairman/Legends|Chairman]] [[San Hill/Legends|San Hill]], [[Archduke/Legends|Archduke]] [[Poggle the Lesser/Legends|Poggle the Lesser]], and the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Count of Serenno/Legends|Count]] [[Dooku/Legends|Dooku]], who wanted to manipulate Grievous into the service of the growing [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Confederacy of Independent Systems]]. Grievous survived with severe injuries and was reconstructed as a [[Cyborg/Legends|cyborg]] at Hill's arrangement. [[Historian/Legends|Historians]] were later divided over whether the crash was the actual cause of Grievous's transformation, as he insisted that he had chosen to be upgraded.

==Description==
{{Quote|All systems failure! I repeat&mdash;|Grievous, following the activation of an ion bomb on the ''Martyr''|<ref name="Eyes" />}}
The ''Martyr'' was a [[Shuttle/Legends|shuttle]]<ref name="Lord of War" /> and [[Troop carrier/Legends|troop carrier]] used by the [[Kaleesh/Legends|Kaleesh]] [[Warlord/Legends|warlord]] [[General/Legends|General]] [[Grievous/Legends|Grievous]].<ref name="Unknown" /> It was [[Color/Legends|gray]] in color and had a box shape with the stern section angling inward, the entrance of which could fold down into a ramp. The ''Martyr'' had two wings with an [[Engine/Legends|engine]] each and a yellow symbol painted on them. The bottom of the [[Starship/Legends|ship]]'s bow had three [[Laser cannon/Legends|laser cannons]], with the middle one being a dual-[[Cannon/Legends|cannon]], while another dual-cannon was placed at the top of the stern. The ''Martyr'' could be [[Pilot/Legends|piloted]] by one person, and the [[Cockpit/Legends|cockpit]] functioned as a detachable [[Escape pod/Legends|escape pod]].<ref name="Eyes" />

==History==
===Crash of the ''Martyr''===
{{Quote|Stand by to eject&hellip;NOW!|Count Dooku, timing the ejection of the ''Martyr''{{'s}} cockpit|<ref name="Eyes" />}}
[[File:KaleeshHolyManWatchesMartyrDeparture-Visionaries.png|thumb|right|200px|The ''Martyr'' departs for its last voyage.]]
By [[29 BBY/Legends|29 BBY]],<ref name="Date" /> Grievous returned to his [[Homeworld/Legends|homeworld]] [[Kalee/Legends|Kalee]] to renew the [[Huk War]] against the [[Yam'rii/Legends|Yam'rii]] [[Species/Legends|species]]. His actions angered his then-employer, [[InterGalactic Banking Clan/Legends|InterGalactic Banking Clan]] [[Chairman/Legends|Chairman]] [[San Hill/Legends|San Hill]], who conspired with [[Geonosian/Legends|Geonosian]] [[Archduke/Legends|Archduke]] [[Poggle the Lesser/Legends|Poggle the Lesser]] and the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Count of Serenno/Legends|Count]] [[Dooku/Legends|Dooku]]<ref name="Unknown" /> to bring Grievous under their control.<ref name="Alien">''[[The New Essential Guide to Alien Species]]''</ref> They planned to [[Sabotage of Grievous' shuttle/Legends|sabotage]] the ''Martyr'' by planting an [[Ion bomb/Legends|ion bomb]] on the ship.<ref name="Unknown" />

At the sacred temple [[Shrupak]],<ref name="Endnotes">{{Blog|abelgpena|53|Endnotes for The Story of General Grievous, Part 1: The Unknown Soldier}}</ref> the ''Martyr'' was [[Fuel/Legends|refueled]]<ref name="Unknown" /> while a [[Unidentified Kaleesh holy man|Kaleesh holy man]]<ref name="Galaxy" /> anointed Grievous in preparation for an attack against the Yam'rii on the planet [[Oben]], joined by his elite [[troop]]s,<ref name="Unknown" /> the eight [[Izvoshra/Legends|Izvoshra]].<ref name="Galaxy" /> Grievous used a ladder to climb up to the cockpit and assured the other Kaleesh he would be successful as long as the ''Martyr'' remained functional. While Grievous was still in flight, Dooku and the [[Droid/Legends|droids]] with him activated the ion [[Bomb/Legends|bomb]], causing the shuttle to falter. Grievous realized that his systems were failing but was unable to act. Just as the ''Martyr'' hit the [[Water/Legends|surface]] of the [[Jenuwaa Sea]], Dooku detonated the ship and forced the cockpit's ejection to save Grievous. Dooku's [[IG-100 MagnaGuard/Legends|IG-100 MagnaGuards]] pulled the severely-wounded warlord from the wreckage.<ref name="Eyes" /> One of the Izvoshra, [[Bentilais san Sk'ar]], survived the explosion,<ref name="Galaxy" /> but all of the other crew were [[Death/Legends|killed]].<ref name="Eyes" />

===Aftermath===
{{Quote|However, as fate would have it, your accident is almost&hellip; a blessing. You see, we have been funding a Geonosian bionic technology project. And you, great general, are the perfect candidate for our experiment&mdash;an experiment that will plunge you back into the heart of battle.|San Hill to Grievous following the ''Martyr''{{'s}} crash|<ref name="Eyes" />}}
[[File:SanHilltransformingGrievous.jpg|thumb|left|300px|San Hill offers Grievous the chance to be rebuilt as a cyborg]]
Grievous awoke with his [[Limb/Legends|limbs]] severely damaged in a [[Bacta tank/Legends|bacta tank]] on the planet [[Geonosis/Legends|Geonosis]], where he was greeted by Hill, who lied that a Banking Clan [[Frigate/Legends|frigate]] had accidentally responded to the beacon from the escape pod and claimed that all of the ''Martyr''{{'s}} other crew had perished in the crash.<ref name="Eyes" /> Grievous was furious to learn that a shuttle crash had injured him so severely after his [[Standard year/Legends|years]] in battle and asked his healers to allow him a warrior's death, reasoning that he would prefer to perish in the vacuum of [[Realspace/Legends|space]] than in a bacta tank.<ref name="Labyrinth">''[[Labyrinth of Evil]]''</ref> Hill instead offered Grievous the chance to become a [[Cyborg/Legends|cyborg]] and regain his abilities as a warrior while serving as a general in the [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Confederacy of Independent Systems]].<ref name="Eyes" /> 

Later [[Historian/Legends|historians]] were divided over whether the shuttle crash was indeed the cause of Grievous's transformation or if the general had voluntarily agreed to the changes<ref name="Warfare">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref> as he claimed.<ref name="Lair">{{TCW|Lair of Grievous}}</ref> The crash of the ''Martyr'' was later mentioned the notes of [[Senior Anthropologist]] [[Mammon Hoole]], which were compiled into a [[The New Essential Guide to Alien Species (book)|full book]] following the conclusion of the [[Swarm War]]<ref name="Aliens">''[[The New Essential Guide to Alien Species]]''</ref> in [[36 ABY]]. It was also acknowledged in a [[The New Essential Chronology (in-universe)|historical document]] compiled by the [[Galactic Federation of Free Alliances]] [[Historical Council]] in that year.<ref name="NEC">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]''</ref>

==Commanders and crew==
{{Quote|A Banking Clan frigate accidentally picked up your escape pod's emergency beacon in the Jenuwaa Sea. Your crew was not so lucky, I'm afraid.|San Hill, lying to Grievous about the ''Martyr''{{'s}} crash|<ref name="Eyes" />}}
The ''Martyr'' was Grievous's personal shuttle,<ref name="CSWE">{{CSWECite|I|369|''Martyr''}}</ref> and he also served as its pilot. Prior to its final flight, the shuttle was refueled by two other Kaleesh. According to Hill, all of the ship's crew were killed when it exploded.<ref name="Eyes" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|How you interpret the story depends largely on what backstory you like. If you believe Grievous was shot down in a shuttle by Dooku and put back together, I think that story is there, it's just that Grievous has invented this new "story" of choosing his alterations. If you don't believe in the EU version of the story or didn't like it, then perhaps this new revelation that Grievous was a warrior whose lust for power made him choose to be altered, suits you better.|Dave Filoni, on the contrasting backstories for Grievous|<ref name="Gilroy and Filoni">{{WebCite|url=http://theforce.net/jedicouncil/interview/henrygilroyanddavefiloni.asp|text=TheForce.Net - Jedi Council - Interviews &#124; Henry Gilroy and Dave Filoni|work=[[TheForce.net]]|archivedate=20200608191740}}</ref>}}
[[File:Martyrdom.png|thumb|right|250px|Grievous's backstory involving the destruction of the ''Martyr'' (pictured) in "The Eyes of Revolution" has been contradicted by other sources.]]
The novel ''[[Labyrinth of Evil]]'', written by [[James Luceno]]<ref name="Labyrinth">''[[Labyrinth of Evil]]''</ref> and published on [[January 25]], [[2005]],<ref name="Amazon">{{RandomHouseOld|url=author/results.pperl?authorid=18222|text=James Luceno}}</ref> was the first source to mention the shuttle crash that led to General Grievous becoming a cyborg.<ref name="Labyrinth" /> The shuttle then made its first full appearance in "[[The Eyes of Revolution]]," a [[Star Wars comic books|comic]] story written and illustrated by [[Warren Fu]] that was published in the anthology ''[[Star Wars: Visionaries]]'',<ref name="Eyes" /> released on [[April 2]], 2005.<ref name="Release">{{Marvel|url=comics/issue/54698/star_wars_visionaries_2005_1|text=Star Wars Visionaries (2005) #1}}</ref> It was first identified as the ''Martyr'' in the article "[[The Story of General Grievous: Lord of War]]," written by [[Abel G. Peña]] and published in [[2006]] on the online service [[Hyperspace: The Official Star Wars Fan Club]].<ref name="Lord of War" /> 

While the comic depicts Grievous being coerced into receiving his [[Cybernetics/Legends|cybernetic]] enhancements as a result of the crash, another slightly conflicting backstory has developed.<ref name="Warfare endnotes">{{Tumblr|subdomain=jasonfry|url=post/22588801475/eg-to-warfare-endnotes-pt-6|name=Jason Fry's Dorkery|text=EG to Warfare: Endnotes Pt. 6}}</ref> In "[[Lair of Grievous]]," the tenth episode of the [[The Clone Wars: Season One|first season]] of the animated television series ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'',<ref name="Lair" /> which premiered on [[December 12]], [[2008]],<ref name="Lair of Grievous Ep Guide">{{SWArchive|url=theclonewars/guide/episode010.html|text=''The Clone Wars'' Episode Guide: Lair of Grievous}}</ref> Grievous insists that he voluntarily chose to have his body cybernetically upgraded.<ref name="Lair" />

[[File:Epguide010.png|thumb|left|300px|In ''The Clone Wars'' episode "Lair of Grievous," Grievous claims that he cybernetically upgraded his body willingly, contradicting the backstory of the crash of the ''Martyr''.]]
Series creator [[Dave Filoni]] stated in a behind the scenes commentary for "Lair of Grievous" that he was aware of the shuttle crash backstory for Grievous in the [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]], but he had chosen to follow ''[[Star Wars]]'' creator [[George Lucas]]'s idea for the character, that Grievous wished for the power and skill of the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] but lacked their [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitivity]], leading him to upgrade his body with cybernetic improvements to compensate.<ref name="Filoni">{{SW|url=video/lair-of-grievous-episode-featurette|text="Lair of Grievous" Episode Featurette}}</ref> The episode's writer, [[Henry Gilroy]], expressed in an interview that he felt that the shuttle crash origin made Grievous into too tragic a villain and believed that him voluntarily becoming a cyborg was more in line with Lucas's vision when he created the character. In the same interview, Filoni felt that fans could choose the version of the story that they believed, with the plausible explanation that Grievous invented the idea that he chose to become a cyborg.<ref name="Gilroy and Filoni" />

When writing the [[2012]] reference book ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]'', [[Jason Fry]] rejected the idea of trying to reconcile both backstories. Instead, he presented the idea of disputes between historians as an [[in-universe]] explanation of the discrepancy.<ref name="Warfare endnotes" />

